1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,340
To use a quotes inside a string,

2

00:00:02,340  -->  00:00:05,300
you can either escape them with a backslash,

3

00:00:05,300  -->  00:00:08,080
like we just learned how to do in the previous lesson,

4

00:00:08,080  -->  00:00:10,860
or use different types of quotes.

5

00:00:10,860  -->  00:00:14,700
In this example, the single quotes wrap the entire string,

6

00:00:14,700  -->  00:00:18,760
and you can put double quotes inside of the string as needed,

7

00:00:18,760  -->  00:00:20,540
or something like this.

8

00:00:20,540  -->  00:00:23,320
In this example, we use double quotes to wrap

9

00:00:23,320  -->  00:00:27,560
the entire string in a single apostrophe shows up inside of the string.

10

00:00:27,560  -->  00:00:30,835
Both of these are acceptable strings according to Python.

11

00:00:30,835  -->  00:00:34,430
With regards to apostrophes inside of strings,

12

00:00:34,430  -->  00:00:36,610
so long as it's a single apostrophe,

13

00:00:36,610  -->  00:00:40,110
then that will not cause an issue or need to be escaped.

14

00:00:40,110  -->  00:00:43,410
If you were to have quotation marks inside of quotation marks,

15

00:00:43,410  -->  00:00:46,890
that is where we would need to have them be escaped,

16

00:00:46,890  -->  00:00:49,205
like we walked through in the last lesson.

17

00:00:49,205  -->  00:00:53,785
May remember our use of multi line strings from the previous lessons.

18

00:00:53,785  -->  00:00:58,320
But let's recap what makes the multi-line string different from a regular string.

19

00:00:58,320  -->  00:01:03,540
As you'll see here, multi-line strings have triple quotes at the beginning,

20

00:01:03,540  -->  00:01:07,800
and at the end, and can span across multiple-lines of text.

21

00:01:07,800  -->  00:01:12,940
Regular strings have the same quotes at the beginning and at the end of the string.
